To start off we have the remote. 
This begins with a custom PCB (LOCATION IN REPO: ). You can order this off of any PCB site. I would suggest https://jlcpcb.com as they are known to be good at production and delivery.
Some of the parts on the PCB are very small, so if you are a beginner, I would recommend having them solder it for you (INSERT GUIDE HERE ON WHAT TO PRESS).



In the wiring diagram, the servos used are not the servos used in the actual build. They are placeholder servo images, but the colours on the wires match up. One can simply assume they are the same ones when it comes to wiring.
There is a piece that connects the motors on the car to the wheel. I would recommend using glue or some other adhesive to minimize any slippage that might occur.
While it might seem strange that the buck converters are not screwed down, it is perfectly fine. As long as you give them some slack in the wires, the solder won't break. The buck converters must also be adjusted manually before being put in. To make sure the step down from 12V to 6V is happening properly.
